segments.text: Okay.
So the fighting was over.
Well, the fighting was substantially over.
The German army had effectively collapsed by that time.

Essentially mop up operations going from where we were on the west bank of the Rhine right on clear up into Yugoslavia and then the unit got sent back to the United States and actually got sent to Camp Swift, Texas, a backdrop.
So that was a shortcoming, just messing around, no excuse for getting wounded in the way I did.
It would have been nice to finish out the war.
Yes, I guess it would.
In retrospect, I don't know whether that would have been unlucky or lucky as it was.
There's so many people qualified
and of course you never know what one day difference at one time or another would have made.
It's just that close.
Retirement is a major change in an individual's life.
Did you retire because of the age?
I went on mandatory retirement for time and grade.
One is allowed five years in grade or a certain number of years for that grade.
But my mandatory retirement was effective because I was five years in the great Brigadier General.
At the time, I was one of those being considered for a major general assignment
commander of the 75th Maneuver Area Command in Houston.
And I guess there was some disappointment that I wasn't selected for that.
But actually I had mixed emotions about it because I had real heavy demands on my civilian job too.
Very few general officers live five minutes from their headquarters.
in the Army Reserve, so I could accomplish this work with a very minimum of time.

And one time previously, I'd turned down an opportunity to be assigned to a general officer position as deputy commander of the 90th Division Artillery, because I didn't feel like I had the time to do it.
There again, it was just a lucky decision.

because the one who was assigned to that position got promoted to Brigadier General, but then his job was, when the whole division was deactivated, he didn't have a job, so he didn't serve in the job for about one year.
So if I'd taken that assignment, I would have had to go to Dallas, Texas to meet with the unit.
That would have taken a good deal more time.
Probably would have detracted from my effectiveness in my civilian job.
I wouldn't have had the position.
I probably would have earned a star alright, but I wouldn't have had the position very long.
I was just lucky that I didn't take that.
So the job down in Houston was a major generalship?
Yes.
And what would you have been doing now?
command the 75th maneuver area command, which is really only about 350 people down there.
So it's basically a smaller command than much ahead, but a higher rank.
Much smaller command, much higher rank, but the responsibilities of the unit are great.
It's just a big headquarters unit that is
prepared to command a maneuver area on mobilization and carried out similar responsibilities on an active duty and active duty for training basis.
Do you remember what your thoughts were on the day that you retired?
Oh, I was happy with my career.
Had no regrets at all.
Plenty of things to do on weekends.
Proud of the people, proud of the status of the unit the way I left it.
Very proud of the man that had been selected to succeed me.
I had campaigned for him.
That's Colonel McIntosh.
I'd selected and tried to bring him along, put him in position.
For every general officer position, of course, any eligible colonel can apply for it.
So here was my deputy right there that we had really a game plan for succession to command of that unit over about five years in the future.
That got telescoped quite a bit because
Carl McIntosh succeeded me and within a year he was Deputy Chief Army Reserves in Washington, a position I feel like I might have had a little bit of influence in helping him get.
And then the man we had picked to succeed McIntosh got to succeed him in just a little over a year, and that was Colonel Len Stewart, a man I had helped to develop
a highly talented person, real able.
I was proud to be present at the ceremony where he got his star.
That would be gratifying.
Oh, the whole thing was just a pleasant trip to me and I really had no regrets on retirement.
Well, let's talk about leadership then.
It's about our final topic.
Could you define leadership?
Well, leadership is a status which one achieves by selection and earns by of course having followers.
fundamental that if one is a leader, you must have followers.
Though it is a status that may be earned by designation or selection by higher leaders or higher authorities, or it can be just given to a person on a volunteer basis by a group of people.
Now, you've been a leader in both civilian and in the military.
Is there a difference?
Basically, I don't think there is.
I think the same traits for success exist in both places.
You know, it's popularized quite often in films to see military leaders like Patton, you know, sort of, come on, over the hill boys, let's go and kick them in the back of the pants.
That kind of,
That idea, do you think that that type of leader is very typical of the armed forces?
Not as much anymore.
It is a very effective form of leadership, very authoritarian, dominant kind of leadership.
But the followers don't, in general, react to that, I believe,
readily as they once did.
We have a higher educated group of people that are rather sophisticated and knowledgeable and different psychology, different expectations.
I don't believe that you can, they're not blind followers that one might expect
to respond best to that style of leadership.
Most people that tried, the way I'm saying it, would fail in that kind of leadership.
Patton was notably successful.
I would say that Paul Bryant, as a football coach, is that type of man.
why it is that they're able to be so effective with that style of leadership.
Certainly it isn't my style.
What is your style of leadership?
I've explained it to my faculty and to my leaders in the Army this way.
have often said that one time I read an article in a wildlife magazine, where the leading sentence in the article was, you can drive a buffalo anywhere he wants to go.
And I believe that's what you can do with professional people and good subordinate leaders in an army.
You can help them achieve whatever it is they really want to achieve.
My style of leadership is to try to give them enough recognition, encouragement, responsibility so that they will want to achieve and try to help them do that.
Support of them.
Well certainly, create opportunity and really, I've often told the successful people
that I never expected them to do anything except a little bit more than they were doing right now.
So I always wanted them to be ambitious and want to achieve just a little bit more.
Give them recognition for it.
Be frank with them about my perception of what their status was, I think.
We must be frank and honest and open about those things.
Okay.
So, so far you've mentioned honesty, being frank, being encouraging.
These to me seem to be values you think leaders should have.
Are there other values that leaders should have?
Well, I certainly believe that a leader must set the example.
I don't believe he can demand anything of those for whom he has responsibility that he wouldn't do himself.
That he has to be willing to work just a little bit harder than those under him to achieve.
So I don't believe he can demand anything of the people for whom he has responsibility that he wouldn't do himself.
I don't believe you can get anybody to do as I say, not as I do.
So that's one other attribute that I think is very important.
I think it is very important that the people receive adequate recognition for what they do.
That they believe that what they do is important.
I wanted to
them to take pride in it.
I want to have pride and I want them to be proud.
Self satisfying.
Achievement.
It seems to me that you're the type of leader that opens paths for people so they can use their open ways for people so they can use their own potentials.
Would you agree with that?
I don't want to put words in your mouth.
I try to
The greatest responsibility a leader has, for instance, one who is department head or whatever, is the selection of the people that will be on his team.
And we have a lot of opportunity for that.
A person to have success must be a good judge of the characteristics of the people that he can choose.
They must have a lot of potential.
He must get a lot of satisfaction out of seeing them develop their potential and keep providing opportunity and stimulus to them.
Is tolerance or flexibility, are those important for a leader?
Well, for some leaders, tolerance is important, but tolerance can also be a fault.
I'm sure George Patton was mighty intolerant.
He had very high standards and he certainly expected people to come up with those standards or else.
So I think that a leader can be too tolerant.
However, I don't think he can be entirely inflexible.
He can't be a martinet.
I certainly believe one hundred percent
you stimulate people to greater accomplishments by encouragement, not punishment.
But you cannot achieve anything at all in the way of improved performance by any form of punishment.
And I believe that a person, that a leader can help
a person to develop by observing and encouraging him in what he does best.
Everybody likes to excel in something and gain recognition for it.
At all times I've tried to fit square pegs into square holes.
where we could all be real pleased with what was accomplished.
Now let's say that the Corps asked you to come over and give a talk to these eighteen, nineteen year old young men on how to become a leader.
What would you say?
Well, I had a talk like that prepared one time.
Oh you did?
staff or somebody that was scheduled to give the commission an exercise was held up by weather some place.
I don't know where it is now.
Do you remember what you said?
No, well I didn't ever have to make it because the weather cleared up and the man did get here, but I was on alert to give the commission an exercise.
Well, I would say that

certain attributes that they must have to achieve leadership roles would be to be dedicated, to set the example themselves for the followers, to demand high standards, and to be generous with recognition for subordinates.
that the leader must be somewhat self-effacing.
If people believe they're being exploited for the benefit of the leader, that is certainly a turn off.
I believe that the leader must be honest and forthright and genuine.
If there is a
ever any suspicion of hypocrisy.
This is definitely a turn off for people.
Then I think I believe I said earlier that the person must know his own goals and objectives and what it takes to achieve those goals based upon experience and observation of others.
Those are some of the characteristics.
The Army does have excellent courses on leadership.
One of the best guys I know of to teach it is Dr. Lannis Hope right here in our Department of Educational Psychology.
He and I organized a leadership school for our engineer brigade.
We asked people to select one person out of each company in the brigade and we put on a leadership course.
for years, so he's excellent on psychology and leadership.
We did use psychological principles at the time.
We were fascinated with Maslow's hierarchy of satisfaction, what gives satisfaction to people.
I think that's been modified somewhat.
I believe I could give them a lecture on leadership based on my experience.
That might seem logical to them.
Now, as a very last topic, there is a number of very important changes in the 1960s here on this campus, as you're well aware of and as you partook in, as a matter of fact.
And as a former student,
I'd like to ask you what you thought of them.
Could you tell us about your role with the women and the blacks and General Rudder and to the Mandatory Corps?
Could you tell us about your ideas on that and your role?
Certainly.
I was privileged to be appointed to a three-person committee by General Rudder.
a committee that was chaired by Dr. Archie Flowers and the Veterinary Public Health Department to consider carefully the matter of enrollment of women in Texas A&M and of compulsory core.
We did a rather thorough study of it and I'm very proud of the fact that the admission of women proceeded exactly according to the way we

recommended that is first that the wives of students and daughters of faculty members be admitted and that females be admitted to those courses that were unique at Texas A&M in all of Texas such as in their medicine if they were otherwise qualified.
We recommended against the mandatory core because that was
military had declined in popularity and we saw that as a handicap to improve stature of Texas A&M University appeal to the general, highly qualified student.
So of course

Those things were also considered by the century study recommendations by a group of 100 highly selected people around the state who served with General Rutter in determining what Texas A&M should be like in 1976.
That was one of the finest activities shaping the future of Texas A&M I think that ever has occurred.
As a matter of fact, most of the gold were exceeded prior to the, I don't know, somewhere between 10 and 15 years.
I don't remember seeing me like that.
It was early 60's when the study was made.
I have been very inspired by the popularity and progress of Texas A&M University since that time.
Now as a corpsman, was it difficult for you to advise against mandatory corps?
Not at all.
Based upon appraisal of the situation, based upon the realization that the corps could be preserved on a voluntary basis,
and be even more professional than it was during the time when it was compulsory.
I had thought that we could go both directions with the increased enrollment.
I believe that the Corps of Cadets right now is good or better than it ever has been in the history of Texas A&M.
I'm certain that it's much better than it was in my time.
So we can have both aspects.
have a very fine Corps of Cadets in military uniform to maintain the traditions of Texas A&M, and we can have a very fine student body outside the Corps of Cadets.
Why do you think the Corps is better?
I've heard others say that the Corps is not as good as it was in the 1930s.
Why do you feel it's better?
Well, I know that the people are better educated.
They're better prepared.
They're better led.
They have a lot more resources.
There is an opportunity for many more leaders.
The organizations are smaller.
They must have three or four times as many active army or active military officers here.
They have much more variety in what they can select, Army, Navy, Air Force, Marines.
I believe that their standards of performance in things that you can see, such as their reviews, are better.
Their appearance is better.
Their uniforms are better.
I just don't know any way where I think they are better than they were in my day.
What about camaraderie?
I'm not 100% prepared to say about that, but I believe it has to be fully as good, if not better, because there is no compulsion.
People that don't like it can get out anytime they want to.
So I'd have to say that the ones that stay in there must like it.
They must be inspired by the camaraderie and association.
Do I have to say that better than it was?
Now I've been at other institutions that are trying to maintain their size, but not grow too fast, just sort of stay fairly steady at 15,000 or 20,000 students.
And Texas A&M goes from about 6,000 to 7,000 students in 1970 to 31,000 in 1960.
to 31,000 in 1980 had done increases perhaps five times.
Why do we have such a growth orientation here at A&M, where at other schools they don't want to grow too fast, at many other schools?
Well, Texas A&M and its role in school
has been one of those institutions, one of really two institutions in the past that were selected for excellence.
University of Texas and Texas A&M.
University of Texas has long had a high enrollment.
The funding of the university is based
standard allocation of funds.
So the more students we have, the more student credit hours we have, the more funds we qualify for, the greater our influence in a former student's organization in all aspects of the state.
And I think that prior to the time that we became quite popular, that many, many of the farmer students were so dedicated to trying to recruit people to come to Texas A&M.
We could hardly believe it when it did get popular.
We got practically overwhelmed with students.
I presume that these are reasons that Texas A&M has wanted to earn and be accorded the kind of recognition they have both for the depth and the size of their contributions and endeavors.
not everybody is interested in the size of the university.
There are many who would prefer to see it half as large as it is now, when life might have been a little less demanding on them.
What's your opinion of another general, Earl Rudder?
Well, I was privileged to serve with Errol Rudder, both in the military and in the civilian.
Errol Rudder was one of those people, quite like Patton, that had a certain charisma, that had the characteristics that I have described of a leader.
A time-tested man, battle-tested,
Started out from a handicapped position when he was placed on active duty at captain level and required to perform against those that had much better training and experience to carry out the job.
In spite of all these handicaps, he did excel.
an honest-to-God legitimate war hero for his leadership of his Ranger Battalion at Pointe du Haut in France, a man who gave me a tremendous amount of encouragement.
And I'd have to say that one of the fine emotional experiences I had is when Mrs. Earl Rudder presented me a set of his stars that I got to wear.
So he's a man I respected greatly and loved.
He gave me the sort of inspiration that I said I think should be given to subordinates.
Recognition, demanding, fair, always wanted the person to be a little more ambitious.
my experience with him.
Like many other, practically every prominent man, I'm sure there were some who were detractors, all right, who might have blamed him.
He judged harshly sometimes.
If you fell out of favor with him, you'd had it, sort of.
